WEBVTT

0
00:00:03.579 --> 00:00:04.260
For years,

1
00:00:04.380 --> 00:00:07.420
the ORW base has been the undisputed

2
00:00:07.420 --> 00:00:09.960
foundation of efficient data center infrastructure.

3
00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:13.369
But the rapid evolution of artificial intelligence has

4
00:00:13.369 --> 00:00:16.670
fundamentally changed the physical requirements of computing.

5
00:00:17.649 --> 00:00:21.010
Next generation AI workloads demand massive scale

6
00:00:21.010 --> 00:00:23.760
up networks and larger silicon footprints.

7
00:00:24.170 --> 00:00:27.290
Engineers need the physical space to distribute

8
00:00:27.290 --> 00:00:30.559
multiple GPUs evenly across the compute tray.

9
00:00:30.969 --> 00:00:33.930
This balanced distribution prevents severe thermal

10
00:00:33.930 --> 00:00:37.369
hotspots and optimizes complex network routing.

11
00:00:38.150 --> 00:00:41.939
Within the boundaries of a traditional 600 millimeter wide rack,

12
00:00:42.270 --> 00:00:45.330
these physical layouts become a severe bottleneck.

13
00:00:46.610 --> 00:00:48.790
The community needed a new standard.

14
00:00:50.470 --> 00:00:53.450
Enter the open rack wide or ORW.

15
00:00:54.750 --> 00:00:56.450
This new specification

16
00:00:56.770 --> 00:00:57.250
literally

17
00:00:57.509 --> 00:01:01.409
doubles the width of the standard rack to 1200 millimeters

18
00:01:01.630 --> 00:01:04.050
or in inches expanding from 21

19
00:01:04.190 --> 00:01:05.250
to 42.

20
00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:09.400
This expansion allows engineers to build massive

21
00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:13.809
interconnected AI platforms without compromising on modularity,

22
00:01:14.199 --> 00:01:17.500
but this shift is about much more than just physical space.

23
00:01:18.349 --> 00:01:22.480
The transition to ORW is a necessary evolution

24
00:01:22.839 --> 00:01:24.870
toward high power racks.

25
00:01:25.239 --> 00:01:28.720
This wider format provides the crucial volume

26
00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:32.279
required to route complex liquid cooling manifolds,

27
00:01:32.839 --> 00:01:35.150
seamlessly integrate high power racks,

28
00:01:35.239 --> 00:01:37.180
shared baseline power shelves,

29
00:01:37.599 --> 00:01:42.480
and support the extreme payload weight of fully populated AI clusters.

30
00:01:43.839 --> 00:01:47.879
By anticipating the physical demands of next generation silicon,

31
00:01:48.239 --> 00:01:51.599
the Open Compute project ensures that scalability

32
00:01:51.599 --> 00:01:54.660
and efficiency remain available to everyone.

33
00:01:55.319 --> 00:01:57.000
Let's take a look inside the new frame.